The European population in South West Africa reflected these relatively favorable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, compared to only 5,336 in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The evolution of Popular Music over the past century has led to the emergence of countless genres, with many of them spawning numerous sub-genres and sub-sub-genres. The genre of heavy metal, in particular, has become one of the most diverse and expressive in the last 40 years. Expressive in its varied emotional range, mostly leaning towards the darker end of the spectrum, heavy metal is also notable for its flexibility, encouraging the creation of new sub-genres and sub-sub-genres. Today, the heavy metal scene is so fragmented, with so many niches, that it's challenging to define what constitutes heavy metal. It has absorbed themes from other genres and been influenced by a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70s, which led to more intense and experimental music. Metal is often characterized by a focus on bass, volume, and theater, with skilled musicianship. It's also known for its dark, visceral qualities, which were relatively new in the music scene at the time and have influenced later generations. Lyrics reflecting this darkness, like those from the Beatles' "Helter Skelter," which is considered one of the first heavy metal songs, exemplify this.

Far before Surrealist artists began painting dreamlike scenes, Henri Rousseau was already artistically dreaming, both figuratively and literally. His 1910 masterpiece, "The Dream," doesn't just depict a woman marveling at a dream landscape but also embodies Rousseau's own aspirations and inner conflicts as an artist. From the start, he yearned for recognition, acceptance, and praise from peers and art enthusiasts, but grappled with the challenge of either conforming to established styles to gain acceptance or forging his own unique path. To fully understand "The Dream" from this angle, one must first know Rousseau's life story. Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, France, his father was a successful tinsmith and hardware dealer. Rousseau lacked formal art training and worked as a toll collector until age 40. His life was marked by loss, including the deaths of his first wife and eight children. Seeking solace, he took up painting. Unlike peers who romanticized peasants in their art, Rousseau was a self-taught folk painter, aspiring to the dreams and hopes of the common people. His late start and lack of formal training made his desire for acceptance understandable. While many talented artists were gaining recognition around him, including Matisse, Rousseau's art was only just beginning to receive notice. Jan Gordon's "Modern French Painters" compares the two: Matisse worked to avoid trite painting, whereas Rousseau strived for conventionality to gain admission to the Artiste Français.

Numerous great minds have proposed a deep connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I contend that there is a fundamental reason for this. As John Keats expressed in his poem "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—That's all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of what we learn in life is through education or experience. Yet, we often appreciate ethics and aesthetics without formal instruction, as Keats suggests. Both ethics and aesthetics aim to describe rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty primarily seek to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful or why an action is moral, rather than to provide rules for judging or creating good art or moral behavior. More importantly, criticism of art or morals can never fully encapsulate what is truly good or beautiful. A discussion about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might focus on elements like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately, these factors don't explain why it's considered good art. When asked about a favorite artwork or literature, we often respond with a phrase like "There's just something about it" before offering more complex or critical explanations. I believe that both art and morality can't be fully reduced to descriptions of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor put it, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way ... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Similarly, ethics shares this transcendent quality. As Wittgenstein stated, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental." I suggest that it is this "something," this ineffable quality, that gives art and morality their most compelling power, and that this transcendental nature of both fields provides a connection between them. I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience them profoundly at a noumenal level, to use a Kantian term. They influence us at a level that can be felt but not fully explained. This connection is even stronger in literature. As McKean noted, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Today's Germany is seen as a powerful, united nation, with a distinctive culture that stretches from the Alps in Munich to the Baltic Sea in Kiel. This culture can be experienced from Cologne along the Rhine, through the heart of Germany, to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. Given its unique cultural blend, it's no surprise that modern Germany is composed of various sources and tribes.

Germania, the ancestral home of the Germans, has an uncertain name origin. While Tacitus claimed it came from the Germanic tribe known as Tungrians, others suggest it may have come from the Gaulish language or the Old Irish word for 'shout'. The Romans, upon encountering these tribes, used the word 'Germanus' to distinguish them from the Gauls they had conquered. Tacitus, in his AD 98 work, "De Origine et situ Germanorum", described the Germans as indigenous, not intermixed with other races. He noted that few would choose to leave Rome for the harsh conditions of Germania, and the Romans primarily sent expeditions to Germania for resources, rather than settling there. The Germanic tribes, appearing during the first century, were located on the Roman Empire's borders, trading their land's produce and military skills with the Romans.

I gazed down, my mind vacuously taking in the scene before me. Without feeling or sound, my practiced awareness scrutinized the object of my study, refusing to connect it to any abstract understanding. Thoughts darted in and out of my mind, so swiftly and effortlessly that it seemed I had no original thoughts, just a fluid awareness of what I was observing. Once, following advice from an artist I worked with, I bought an art book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." This book teaches everything from understanding a pencil to how the brain interprets lines. One technique it teaches is to frame a picture with a square, transforming a complex scene into a simpler one.

At that moment, staring at the bowl in front of me, I couldn't mentally place that artistic frame. Overwhelmed and awestruck, all I could do was stand and stare in admiration. Artists like Picasso, Monet, and the Italian Renaissance masters inspired me. Before me was the start of my own artistic journey, what I would later call "Work in Brown."

My fingers reached for my chosen tool, muscles tensing and relaxing as my hand moved through space, giving shape to my will. Water swirled peacefully, clear and calm. Matter flaked off and disappeared into nothingness. My hand hit the toilet handle again, more anxiously this time, but the offending brown mass remained stuck. Grip tightening, I frowned at the mess someone had left for the cleaning crew at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more moments of quiet reflection, and I reached for the toilet paper, wrapping it like an oven mitt. Standing upright, then bending at the waist, my hand gently dipped into the bowl, mimicking a mother reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey....

Teenagers are dying due to driving. Several interconnected factors lead to this alarming trend among the youngest American drivers. The National Institutes of Health note that one aspect of the issue is that the teen brain isn't fully equipped to handle driving hazards. Lack of experience also plays a significant role. This lack of experience results in more fatal accidents, as well as increased incidents of vehicle rollover, speeding, and driving off the road. Teenagers tend to fare worse when driving with peers, which they frequently do. A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center found that the age of passengers correlated with the number of traffic accidents. California and other states have implemented temporary provisional licenses to limit hours teens can drive and prohibit other minors as passengers. However, these are merely temporary fixes. The core issue is that, as a collective, young drivers are statistically unable to handle the risks and responsibilities of driving. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman argues that even 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman's research indicates that teens under 19-20 often engage in risky behaviors for the thrill of it. Therefore, it's sensible to delay driving until this tendency subsides. If we continue to grant driver's licenses to young teens, we'll likely see an escalation in deadly accidents and a significant increase in deaths in the coming years. By 2010, the Baby-Boomer generation's children will be eligible to drive, adding millions of new teen drivers to the roads. Legislation to address this issue would be relatively simple. Schools could continue to offer driver's education, but no one under 18 could legally drive. Provisional permits could still be issued, with a set number of practical driving hours required. The number of hours could be based on the current requirements in most states. A uniform, national law would be a reasonable and effective way to protect teens across the country. The legislation I propose is not a new concept.

While browsing the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I decided to watch all the trick films, totaling fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films employ clever editing to create illusions. My study primarily examined the visual styles of most trick films and the unique traits of a few later films. Typical trick films at the turn of the century were set-bound, staged in a frontal proscenium with no camera movement, and used long or medium shots. They adhered to the rule that one shot equals one film. However, some films at the start of the twentieth century deviated from these norms by incorporating multiple shots. One common feature among trick films is their interior set filming within a frontal proscenium frame. The camera does not move to follow characters or objects but stays in a fixed position, influenced by theater and vaudeville traditions. Characters in these films primarily move side-to-side and rarely walk towards or away from the camera. For instance, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right and move horizontally, exiting the frame without the camera following them. This setup leads to long and medium shots, with close-ups never used, reminiscent of theater and vaudeville performances where the audience could see the whole performance at once. Most early trick films followed the rule where one shot equals one film, limiting their length to around a minute or less and their dramatic or narrative content to short vaudeville-style tricks like magic or disappearing acts. Notably, in trick films, one conceptual shot can consist of several physical shots combined to create illusions, such as in The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), where a close inspection reveals that the "head" shot is part of a combination of physical shots.

John Taylor, hailing from Caroline, was an early and passionate advocate for Republicanism. Despite being primarily an agriculturalist and a brief political career, his stance on personal freedom and government was unyielding. His deep commitment to agrarianism shaped his views on governance, including his opinions on sovereignty, constitutionality, and the judicial system.

Taylor saw this as an opportune moment for the United States to establish an ideal governance system, given the lack of restrictive traditions. He believed in the inherent interdependence of natural human rights, which should be beyond the government's grasp. He also argued that in a civilized society, power should not be left to the physically or mentally formidable, as is seen in a "state of nature." To achieve this, a government must account for the dual nature of human goodness and evil.

Taylor favored a government founded on moral principles that protected private property, promoted agriculture, and discouraged capitalism. He believed that such principles ensured fairness, regardless of the administration's inherent avarice and self-interest. Self-interest, he argued, was only harmful when it led to sub-societies exploiting others. A good government was essential to contain human evil and maintain a balance of principles.

Taylor, like many of his contemporaries, advocated for a strict adherence to the Constitution, calling for a minimal Federal government with powers strictly defined by the Constitution. He was wary of an extensive Federal government due to its potential for despotism and believed that a literal interpretation, without considering the writers' intent, could easily become corrupt. He also considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more clearly states the nation as a union of sovereign states rather than one nation.

Referring to Figure 17, there was a significant decrease in commuter log submissions during the third month of the project. The reason for this drop is unclear, but it could be attributed to several factors. The onset of winter in a New England campus leads to a reduction in bicycle and pedestrian commuters. December, being the end of the fall semester, is also a busy period when students and faculty are focused on completing coursework and grading, potentially causing the commuter log to fall off their radar. Additionally, December marks the start of the holiday season, followed by a month-long break for both students and faculty, during which many do not need to commute. Furthermore, the return of classes for the spring semester in late January may also contribute to the low number of submissions in February. The decline in submissions could also be a natural consequence of the project's initial enthusiasm waning over time. To rejuvenate the project, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which resulted in an increase in log submissions. Therefore, one of the main challenges faced was sustaining project momentum despite the natural decrease in engagement and the specific challenges posed by holiday and semester breaks in higher education. Another key challenge was the entrenched preference for driving, which is deeply ingrained in our culture. To encourage alternative commuting modes, various incentives were offered, such as gift certificates to local businesses. Although these incentives were effective, it would have been interesting to see if larger prizes, like bicycles or hybrid/electric cars, could have further boosted participation. The value of the prizes remained constant throughout the project, but increasing the value over time, such as announcing additional large prizes in December and January, might have contributed to increased engagement.

An ETF (exchange-traded fund) is a financial instrument designed to mimic an index, a commodity, or a collection of assets, similar to an index fund, but with the added flexibility of trading like a stock on an exchange. ETFs offer diversification like index funds, with the additional advantages of short selling, margin buying, and purchasing as little as one share per transaction. While ETFs have lower expense ratios than most mutual funds, there is a trade commission for each ETF transaction, similar to stock trading. One of the key advantages of ETFs is the wide variety of available funds. It is essential for savvy investors to assess whether these benefits, such as diversification, genuinely exist and to what extent. For this analysis, we will examine the ETF IHF and compare it to its top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of the ETF's assets, to determine if owning a single ETF yields comparable benefits to owning a diversified portfolio of these ten stocks, and whether there are more optimal configurations of these stocks.

To assess the ETF, we focus on the top ten holdings, as including all holdings would be too complex. Below are the top 10 holdings and their percentage of total assets.

To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF, we use the current percentage of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate their contribution to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio consisted of these 10 stocks in the proportions held by the ETF. These calculations are presented in the chart below.

From the chart, it is clear that a portfolio of the top 10 holdings would yield a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, representing a 16% increase in returns. Additionally, the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF. Based on these results, it appears that a portfolio of the top 10 holdings could provide higher returns with lower Beta. However, it is possible that the means of these two portfolios are not significantly different from each other.

To determine if the portfolios are statistically different, we calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their combined standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Dream-land, a renowned poem by Edgar Allan Poe, features the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56. This term, traced back to Virgil by Mabbott, refers to an island north of Britain, a boundary of the known world to the ancient Greeks. Though Virgil used it, a more contemporary reference is Poe's interest in German authors and, specifically, his familiarity with Goethe's works. Karl J. Arndt notes similarities between Poe's "Dream-Land" and Goethe's "The King of Thule," suggesting Poe's imitation of the latter. Goethe's "Faust," published in two parts (1808 and 1832), includes the poem "The King of Thule" about a bereaved king who loses his will to live after his wife's death. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" share striking parallels, with the latter's speaker mirroring the former's melancholic themes of loneliness and despair. Poe references "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum," again using "Thule" as bookends for "Dream-Land." The poems can be seen as companion pieces, with the speaker of "Dream-Land" seemingly stepping into Goethe's world. Poe admired Goethe, likely influenced by his appreciation for Tennyson and the widespread reproductions of Goethe's works.

In California, could a customer who suffered injuries from slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages by proving that the store manager acted with malice? The judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer's punitive damage claim outright. To justify punitive damages, a plaintiff must show that the defendant's actions were intentional and that the conduct was outrageous. Palmer can argue that Martin should have been aware of the potential danger of the spill, given the multiple prior incidents and his failure to clean it within half an hour. While her argument may not be airtight, it is reasonable considering the six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009 and Martin's inaction. On October 13, 2009, employees informed Martin about the spill, but he said he was on a dinner break and couldn't handle customer complaints. By 5:30 pm, Palmer slipped and fell, sustaining a serious back injury. Palmer is now suing for damages, and we are considering filing a motion to dismiss the punitive damage part of her claim. Under California law, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a non-contractual breach if the defendant acted with oppression, fraud, or malice. The statute defines malice as conduct intended to cause harm or, in the absence of intent, conduct that is despicable and committed with a willful disregard for the rights or safety of others. Courts often deem conduct malicious when the defendant was aware of the probable dangerous consequences and deliberately failed to avoid them.

Around four years ago, I attended a course on Islam at CBC. One of the primary topics of debate was whether Islam is inherently adversarial. I find this question even more pertinent today than it was at the time. Reflecting on events since 9/11, I've noticed a shift in American media's perception of Islam, ranging from hostility towards extremists to an almost exaggerated tolerance. For instance, in 2001, it would have been unimaginable to have a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, who openly acknowledged his family's Muslim background.

The Prophet Muhammad's biography captivated me, initially, but I've found discrepancies between the historical Muhammad and the depicted character. According to my understanding of history, Muhammad supposedly forced conversions, conquering tribes and imposing Islam upon them. However, the biography portrays him as a martyr, misunderstood and humble, who gradually attracted followers through his teachings. This narrative, to me, diminishes Jesus' miracles and life, appearing to ascribe to Muhammad the traits and deeds of Jesus.

Moreover, many stories in the biography seem to serve as 'proof' of voluntary conversions, often relayed through third-party accounts, which I found unconvincing. This approach, while aiming to authenticate the stories, actually weakens them, making them seem less credible.

What troubles me most about this work is how it elevates Muhammad, portraying him as a godly, humble, wise, and gentle figure. However, historical records contradict this portrayal, suggesting Muhammad was not a gentle or humble man. I wonder if today's Muslims are aware of the true historical context behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus, along with his beliefs during his lifetime, were initially set aside as Christian thought evolved after his life. Observing this historical trajectory, we notice a consistent drift away from Christianity's origins. Contemporary society exhibits a rising awareness and unprecedented progressivism. While conservative individuals will likely resist any shifts beyond their established beliefs, they may not significantly impact the broader population. Among Christians, a growing historical consciousness will emerge in the future, fueling a desire to distinguish the doctrines added to Christianity from its original intentions. This trend may take decades or centuries, but it is inevitable: Christian history will reverse, returning to its foundational form. A movement will gain momentum, stripping away layers of doctrine like rewinding a clock, until only Jesus' original teachings remain. When this shift sweeps through the U.S. and Europe, influencing large populations to worship as if living in Jesus' time, the church will maintain its influence. However, with the theological "clock" moving backward, extreme diversity in Christendom will give way to increasing uniformity of belief and practice among different regions, denominations, and divisions. History is filled with such reversals, such as Christians being persecuted by the Roman Empire before the empire became Christian, and the transition from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The upcoming reversal in Christianity will seek its roots and undo diversity. This process will be facilitated by interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically, not literally. What has occurred since Jesus' time?
   If we delve deeply into history, we find that Judaism was the foundational theology for Christianity. Monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were at Christianity's core by the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not unified, with groups including Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

Upton Sinclair's The Jungle illustrates that, at heart, people are inherently selfish and self-interested. They primarily focus on improving their own lives at the expense of others. This novel underscores this theme through various means. One clear demonstration is the behavior of factory owners and managers, who are solely concerned with growing their businesses and factories, disregarding the consequences and harm caused by their actions. Sinclair vividly portrays the extensive pollution generated by factories, with soot-filled skies and waste-filled rivers. Despite these environmental hazards, the owners exhibit no regard for the well-being of people or animals. Similarly, workers are treated as expendable, forced to labor under harsh conditions and without adequate compensation or benefits. The time period depicted in The Jungle lacks worker protections, allowing managers and owners to exploit their employees. Workers were essentially enslaved, toiling in harmful conditions with no recourse or aid, and were often left unemployed by the whims of their employers. As a result, they were subjected to immoral and exploitative conditions, akin to those experienced by slaves.

Various authors employ different strategies to evoke specific feelings or attitudes in readers towards significant subjects, with some techniques being more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald employs many of these methods in his novel "The Great Gatsby". Sometimes, he pairs unusual adjective-noun combinations to create a certain atmosphere around a subject. At other times, he assigns symbolic meaning to colors and then uses these symbols for the same purpose. Fitzgerald uses this latter technique extensively with colors such as gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In "The Great Gatsby", Fitzgerald establishes meaning for white/gray and red/pink and later employs these meanings to evoke feelings around important objects.

The meaning Fitzgerald assigns to white/gray is uniformity, with white representing a higher social status and gray signifying age and decay. He introduces this concept early in the novel through frequent use of both colors. For instance, Daisy and Jordan are consistently "in white" (8), everyone at Gatsby's party wears white—Nick in "white flannels" (41), Tom in a "white shirt" (36) when meeting Myrtle, and Catherine is "powdered milky white" (30). The only deviation is when Nick observes Gatsby's party, where "the halls... are gaudy with primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald further reinforces the uniformity of these colors by applying them to ordinary subjects: Nick travels "down the white chasms of lower New York" (56), the names at Gatsby's parties are "gray names" (61) on his timetable, and Catherine's apartment is part of a "long white cake of apartment-houses" (28). He also describes mundane people or places in white or gray: Jordan and Daisy share a "white girlhood" (19), there are "gray cars" and "gray land" (23) in the valley of ashes, and the Italian child on the train and the dog-seller are both "gray" (26, 27).

After assigning significant meaning to white/gray, Fitzgerald uses them to signify unimportance or uniformity around certain subjects. This technique begins with Daisy. After a lengthy period without notable use of these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in a "little white roadster" (74), causing readers to view her more as a uniform addition, something Gatsby desires (74). Fitzgerald employs this technique further around Daisy to emphasize her uniformity, such as with a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" (18) and her being in a "white" (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is known for its agricultural productivity due to its warm, sunny climate. Popular crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, stone fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a thriving market for organic community supported agriculture products in the San Diego area, with many local groups having long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand. Many organic farms offer tours of their operations and provide access to hiking trails and birdwatching areas. This type of operation allows landowners to benefit from government programs while enhancing habitat, promoting recreational activities, and creating opportunities for farm tours and educational programs. Organic farming often results in greater biodiversity due to the absence of chemicals in the soil and water, but it also has higher costs, including increased labor and management to control pests and weeds, and potential higher crop losses. Non-organic practices beneficial to wildlife, such as planting cover crops and managing species, may also incur additional costs. Therefore, landowners might seek financial assistance or expertise to maximize both profits and habitat quality. The chosen property is a 160-acre parcel near the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California, which includes chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland adjacent to the Cleveland National Forest. It is part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion, currently home to over a hundred threatened and endangered plant and animal species, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher. This land has a rich history, having been inhabited by Native Americans for centuries and later used by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s.

Culture significantly influences the dynamics of any negotiation. Defined both by its characteristics and what it lacks, culture is not uniform, nor is it universal. Stereotypes like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" oversimplify the complexity of cultures. A better approach for negotiators is to understand how cultural attitudes impact specific negotiations. When faced with a foreign culture, people tend to relate it to their own, often leading to comparisons. Understanding a foreign culture or mindset can involve examining its history or acknowledging its biases. Rather than trying to change or judge a culture, it's crucial to accept it and operate within its norms, especially when one has less power. Respecting the host culture's traditions and beliefs can help overcome cultural barriers and advance negotiations. It's also worth noting that company cultures within a nation can differ significantly. These cultures can be seen in dress codes, communication styles, hiring practices, and values regarding work-life balance or philanthropy, as can be observed in the diversity within American corporate culture. Cultural values are vital as they explain the 'why' behind a culture's behaviors. For instance, cultures that prioritize saving face or communal harmony will not tolerate public shaming, while others might prioritize hard bargains. Negotiators should familiarize themselves with these generalities before negotiating but also learn about their opponent's personal background to enhance effectiveness.

The fool states, "There is no God." This assertion is found in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and serves as the opening of St. Anselm's argument for God's existence. Both St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas defend this belief, so we will assume they both believe in the biblical God. We'll examine their arguments, but we must first acknowledge that both their arguments are centered around the same concept of God. For simplicity, let's proceed under the assumption that they both believe in the biblical God. However, neither argument presents a comprehensive basis for believing in God.

St. Anselm's argument involves exploring faith as a means of understanding, suggesting that God's existence can be understood within one's own mind. He posits that because God is within our understanding, it's impossible to truly conceive of his nonexistence. The proof for God, he claims, is found within our own thoughts. This concept, though complex and sometimes unclear, essentially argues that our own minds contain the truth about God's existence, making external evidence unnecessary. This is often referred to as faith in Christian texts.

Thomas Aquinas, on the other hand, believes that God's existence can be proven through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith. This approach is advantageous for evangelism, as it allows for logical persuasion of new converts. Aquinas presents five logical arguments to support the existence of God: the argument from change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for his existence. For example, if you know you're missing one puzzle piece, you can infer its existence and features without seeing it directly.

Around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince destined to become known as Buddha was born. Throughout his life, he abandoned the world and attained enlightenment, with his teachings laying the foundation for Buddhism, the most traditional branch of which is Theravada Buddhism. Established roughly 2,500 years ago, Buddhism has evolved significantly, evident in Sri Lanka's Theravada community, which observes an annual water-cutting ritual. monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, which holds religious significance despite Buddha not having taught about such festivals. This evolution encompasses both superficial traditions and the core beliefs of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, encompassing both monks and laypeople, has altered its doctrinal principles over time due to both internal and external, hostile and benign influences.

This discussion employs several terms frequently: internal forces, originating from Buddhist community members regardless of their monastic status; external forces, coming from non-Buddhists; hostile forces, those that harm or intend to harm the Buddhist community; and benign forces, those that do not wish to harm or help the community but may do so incidentally.

First, let's examine the fundamental teachings of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists find refuge in the Triple Gem—the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma includes the Tripitaka, the three baskets of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for life, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka explores Buddhist metaphysics, such as Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Recognizing these concepts helps escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. Along with this, lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) also come to an end when one becomes enlightened. The Vinaya Pitaka sets forth rules for laypeople (five precepts) and monks (many more rules). The core doctrinal notion is the Four Noble Truths: Dukkha (life is suffering), that attachment causes suffering, and that suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico once engaged in a long-standing rivalry that lasted for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The rivalry reached its peak during the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States emerged victorious and gained control of Texas and the American Southwest (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31). Over the years, numerous incidents occurred between the two nations, with the rivalry subsiding just before World War I. The root causes of the rivalry included religious, cultural, and traditional differences, as well as competing economic interests (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31). This is a common phenomenon among neighboring countries, many of which have long-standing rivalries due to shared borders and conflicting interests (Pletcher 1977, p. 41). The United States and Mexico, like Mexico and Cuba, have been significant diplomatic rivals for the United States, while many other Latin American nations have maintained good relations with the U.S. (Pletcher 1977, p. 41). Religious differences, a persistent issue throughout history, played a significant role in the rivalry between the two nations (Frahm 2001, p. 86). Similar to the Cold War's ideological struggle between the United States and the Soviet Union, the rivalry between the U.S. and Mexico was both ideological and based on each nation's vital interests, with the ideological struggle rooted in religious preferences (Schmitt 1974). This distrust was inherited from the historical conflict between the English and Spanish, making the establishment of cordial foreign relations challenging (Schmitt 1974). Diehl and Goerts (2000) identify 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during this period, most of which were territorial issues involving border raids and frontier problems (Diehl and Goerts 2000; Schmitt 1974, p. 97). The rivalry began to wane as Mexico grew increasingly dependent on the United States, and it ultimately ended when American interests shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico (Schmitt 1974, p. 109-110).

Fifteen years ago, I unexpectedly became disabled due to an illness I was unaware of. At the time, I was a nurse. I chose this profession as a way of gaining the safety and security I lacked as a child. The phrase "people will always get sick; you'll always be able to find work" was a mantra I heard often while growing up, leading me to choose nursing despite my dreams of becoming a scientist or journalist. Now, at 46 and single, I find myself unable to work, living on Social Security Disability with little to my name after 15 years. The uncertainty and daily struggles have taken a toll on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Yet, I know for certain that I could not have survived these years without the support of my family and a few kind friends. No matter how strong one may feel, real crises leave one feeling weak and helpless. My point is that life is full of emergencies, both big and small, and some challenges are too great to face alone. While I agree that we should not rely solely on a faltering government, I believe we should learn to trust and help each other instead of relying on self-sufficiency. Our forefathers' resilience during hard times was not due to rugged individualism, but rather compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources. So, while I advocate for preparedness, such as having a disaster kit and food supplies, I also emphasize the importance of building community and getting to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms develop in specific ways? Are there constraints that shape the path of evolutionary change? Despite D’Arcy Thompson’s 1917 statement that even simple organic forms are difficult to define mathematically, recent advancements in mathematical modeling have been applied to mollusk shell development through both ontogeny and phylogeny. Our research focuses on using mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, alongside experimental studies, to understand the mechanisms driving evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to identify quantitative parameters that can be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies, which were then entered into the CerioShell software. We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies to interpret the bounds of possible morphological change in Prunum, and these results are being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to better comprehend macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be visualized as a tube that twists through 360 degrees of space. These twists, known as whorls, spiral around an imaginary central axis called the columella. The rate at which whorls expand can vary, with a continuous line separating each whorl and referred to as a suture. The largest whorl, known as the body whorl, is typically the last. The spire consists of all the whorls except the last, with the apex at the tip and the base at the opposite end. The animal exits the shell through an opening called the aperture. Shells can be viewed from different orientations: apical (viewing the apex), basal (viewing the base), apertural (viewing the aperture), or abapertural (viewing the aperture from the opposite side).

A method for counting whorls involves viewing the shell from the apical perspective and determining where the first suture begins. Drawing a line from this point divides the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line, estimated to a quarter of a whorl. Shells can be seen as a series of apertures that move through time and space as the animal builds its shell. The path of the aperture can be tracked using coordinates of the center of each whorl's aperture, along with the horizontal and vertical radii. This path can be graphically and mathematically represented, allowing for parameter adjustments to modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

For the past decade, neonatal and infant mortality rates in Indonesia have shown little change. While the country is making strides towards achieving many Millennium Development Goals, such as improving water and sanitation, the progress in child and maternal health is lagging behind. The underlying causes of these issues will be explored below, highlighting the need to bolster the healthcare system rather than focus solely on specific interventions.

Indonesia has seen an increase in the number of births attended by skilled healthcare workers, with 72% now meeting this target. However, this category includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot provide medical interventions during complicated pregnancies, contributing to high maternal death rates from causes like hemorrhage. This progress is misleading and points to the need for further improvements. There has also been a decrease in the percentage of children under five who receive treatment for diarrhea from a healthcare professional, with postnatal care data showing low rates across the country.

Cesarean-section rates remain low at around 4%, with a stark disparity between urban (7%) and rural (2%) areas, indicating a lack of equitable access to healthcare services. Additionally, there is a significant gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, with the poorest facing higher barriers to access healthcare, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

In considering the next steps to enhance neonatal and maternal care, the key question is how to best address the service gaps. Should Indonesia focus on developing targeted programmatic approaches or strengthening the entire healthcare system, including pre- and post-natal care for mothers and children? While programmatic interventions have clear, manageable objectives and can yield faster results, they can also lead to funding and human resource imbalances, with resources being concentrated in well-funded programs. Moreover, running multiple, uncoordinated programs can result in overlapping services, increased paperwork, and inefficiencies.

Victorian novels are renowned for their meticulous attention to detail and focus on the aristocracy of the era. Two exceptions from this literary tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both novels incorporate an element of mystery and the unusual, which is atypical of the period, and this enhances the characters in each work by providing deeper insights into their motivations and emotions. In one scene, Oliver experiences a series of confusing and unsettling visions. He hears Sikes and Crackit arguing, as if he were still with them, and then suddenly wakes to the sounds of gunshots and chaos, being carried away by an unseen force. Throughout these vivid hallucinations, Oliver feels a constant, tormenting pain, highlighting his lack of control over the events unfolding. When he revisits the shooting in chapter 28, he relives the experience as if in a dream, further emphasizing his helplessness. The passage underscores Oliver's despair and the sense that his misfortune is not of his own doing. This scene also suggests that Oliver has little control over his circumstances, even when his life is at stake, and hints at a growing sense of defeat, as if Fagin has broken his spirit.

A few years ago, I worked in an after-school program tutoring elementary students. I aimed to assist them in any subject they were struggling with, but my strongest subjects were English and reading. One of the instructors asked me to help a boy named Adrian (around third or fourth grade) who had significant difficulty reading. It soon became clear that something was amiss; he could pronounce some letters correctly while others were completely off. He was Latino, but spoke perfect English. Our struggles continued until I met his mother. During a babysitting session for a few stragglers while the rest of the group was on a field trip, his mother walked in. She only spoke Spanish. With my limited Spanish knowledge, we managed to communicate, and it hit me that Adrian could read but didn't know the English alphabet well. I hope he's doing better now. I share this story to highlight the issue of language barriers in schools, especially in California. It's not always as apparent as we think. A child speaking perfect English can still struggle with reading. I believe everyone agrees this problem exists, so how do we address it? In Adrian's case, the solution was simple: tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for children with limited English, the solution is more complex. There isn't a one-size-fits-all answer. The key lies in combining dual language systems, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes, and other methods. The dual language system, for instance, can benefit all children, not just those whose first language is Spanish. Studies show that children in two-way bilingual education programs perform better academically. The idea is often met with fear that it's a waste of resources, but that's unfounded. If we made these programs the norm rather than the exception, all children would benefit. To implement this, we don't need all teachers to be bilingual; special aides or tutors who are bilingual would suffice.

From childhood, many of us are exposed to the idea of something greater than ourselves, something that's beyond our understanding. Some are taught about it in church or temple, while others seek answers within themselves. Some readily embrace the beliefs passed down by their families, but others reject them outright, believing that there's nothing beyond our personal experiences. No matter what path we choose, we strive to define our spirituality through our unique perspectives. We search for a guiding light to lead us out of the darkness into the light.

“A cardinal,” my father replied when I asked him about his favorite bird. We sat on the porch, listening to the rain batter the tin roof, smoking our cigarettes. The gutters directed the rain towards the plants around the porch, drowning them. He gazed into the rain, a look somewhere between searching and reminiscing. He had lost weight and his clothes hung loosely on him. His hair was thinner than I remembered. He kept his gaze on the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt isolated, frightened, and unable to discuss how much I would miss him, as talking about it would make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, moved my chair closer, and joined him in watching the rain of the June twilight.

My father passed away in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemotherapy and radiation had prolonged his life slightly, but he continued to suffer. I couldn't understand the purpose of this. In the dark, I didn't pray. If God existed, I thought, he had stopped listening to me a long time ago.

I didn't want to witness my father's passing. I couldn't watch the life that created me end. I wanted to remember him by his life, not his death. I was his only child, and I knew he wouldn't want me to be a spectator at his end. I curled up in my bed for three days, waiting for the news. No one even called me.

The traditional "Gothic Novel," as described by Ian Watt in The Rise of the Gothic Novel, is essentially an "old-new oxymoron." It has been both criticized and celebrated, accused of lacking depth and praised for its 'terrible sublime' atmosphere (Burke). The original Gothic Novel, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, blended elements from both "ancient" and "modern" romances to establish the proto-Gothic genre and a new form of literary expression. Walpole incorporated "old" theatrical elements and 'new' nature mimicry into this "Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws heavily upon medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. When Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto, the term "gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and time periods, often seen as archaic or unsophisticated compared to "modern" societal and literary advancements. The blend of the more theatrical "Gothic" style and the novel's personal character focus allowed Gothic to remain relevant for centuries, seeming both obsolete and fresh to readers far removed from the original works.

Supply chain management comprises the sequence of operations involved in moving goods from the point of customer order through the stages of raw materials, production, and distribution to the final customer. The concept of supply chain management was introduced by Keith Oliver in 1982. It involves planning, executing, and overseeing the activities within the supply chain to meet customer needs promptly and efficiently. Key elements of a supply chain include production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers utilize these elements to optimize customer service. The production stage is the first step, forming the basis for the entire supply chain. It involves determining the timing, purpose, location, and method of production. Managers must understand customer preferences, which can be deduced from market analysis. After assessing market trends and customer demand, managers decide which products to produce and in what quantities. They also determine the most suitable production location, considering factors such as volume and quality, while keeping customer satisfaction in mind. Post-decision, managers focus on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Production is crucial for the supply chain, and meticulous planning is essential to avoid time and cost inefficiencies. For instance, I worked at Wal-Mart and Target. Both retailers have meticulously designed processes and layouts for every aspect of their operations, including employee uniforms and shipment receipts. These structured processes ensure smooth operations and clear expectations.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply. Supply refers to strategic decisions that define a facility's core capabilities and the need for outsourcing partnerships. Companies may have multiple production divisions for a single product, each with distinct equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers must select the most suitable division for each product process. Outsourcing can be employed to enhance velocity, which is the ability to deliver quality and flexibility while controlling costs or maintaining cost-efficiency.

Adolf Hitler has been spotted in Burma, according to the sign held by Ellen Page, the lead actress from Juno. Page stands on a street corner in Burma, the sign in her hand bearing a stark message written in black marker. Burma, or Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation governed by a military regime that took power in 1962 following a coup d'état. In 2007, a series of public protests, dubbed the "Saffron Revolution" due to the robes worn by the protesters, erupted, led by Buddhist monks. The demonstrations, initially peaceful, turned violent as the government cracked down, leading to military invasions of monasteries and suppression of foreign journalists. A Japanese photographer, Kenji Nagai, was murdered on September 27, 2007, for simply covering the protests. The official death toll stands at 13, but a defected colonel claims many more were killed, with estimates in the thousands.

This is a grim reminder that governments seeking to suppress dissent and maintain absolute power are not a new phenomenon. Throughout history, figures such as Roman emperors, Japanese imperialists, and even the current U.S. president, George W. Bush, have claimed divine or quasi-divine authority. Notable incidents include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students were killed in the thousands, according to Chinese Red Cross reports, and the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militias, with government support, systematically murdered Tutsis and political moderates. The Holocaust, a chilling example of Hitler's Third Reich, saw the widespread murder of individuals of Jewish descent.

Duke Ellington's enduring impact on jazz is significantly attributed to his long career and his unique ability to direct his orchestra. While his piano playing is often understated in his compositions, as a composer, Ellington excelled in creating intricate pieces that highlighted the individual talents of his band members. He set up a framework where soloists could freely improvise, while also writing tightly arranged pieces and phrases that showcased the specific styles of his musicians to enhance the musical themes. This approach also emphasized the overall tone of the orchestra, producing distinctive and original sounds for each piece. Ellington's mastery of individual band members' sounds and how they blended together in an ensemble allowed him to create some of the most innovative and brilliant works in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington's sound and innovation by mentioning "Creole Love Call," an early example of Ellington using the voice as a jazz instrument. This piece demonstrates his ability to add texture and color without lyrics, as well as his skill in complementing the style of his soloists. The song has six choruses, each featuring a different soloist or ensemble section:
Chorus 1: A call and response between voice and reeds, starting smooth and melodic, then moving to a rougher sound.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo that builds on the main melody and emphasizes blue notes.
Chorus 3: A sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, accompanied by a soft syncopated piano line.
Chorus 4: The full band repeats the first chorus in a call and response format with brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus, where reeds start the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with the voice using the "growl" technique for soloing.
Tag: A brief vocal run is followed by a dissonant trombone ending.

Ellington's use of the voice in "Creole Love Call" is an example of a characteristic style that permeates his work. In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill in tight orchestration with his keen ear for tone color. A call and response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley's playing and the instrumental aspects of Cox's voice to create a rich, complementary sound. "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" extends these ideas, with Ellington using Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton to effectively introduce the melody on muted trombone.

She had long felt an unmet yearning, which persisted from age 14 to 17. Initially, she craved something unspecified; now, she desired a connection with someone, yet no one appealed to her. She'd pondered this puzzle for years but found no satisfactory answers. Ordinarily, her life was peaceful, her parents calm and rarely argued. Today, however, was different. She heard her mother crying out in pain and rushed to her, finding her injured. She assisted her mother, who asked to be taken to the hospital. At the hospital, she was greeted by the scent of disinfectant and fear, but she was too focused on her mother's care. It turned out her mother had fallen from a step stool while fetching a vase.

This research aimed to demonstrate the link between adherence to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", and reduced risks of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a revised version of the Med diet, characterized by increased intake of plant-based foods (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (in comparison to saturated fats), and fish, along with decreased consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permissible.

Previously conducted studies have shown an inverse relationship between adherence to the Med diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular mortality (CVD), and an intervention trial illustrated the Med diet's superiority over a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. These prior studies did not delve into stroke or stroke mortality.

This study tracked 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who participated in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study involving 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. The authors calculated an aMed diet score six times from 1984 to 2004, using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) that assessed nutrient intake over the preceding year. Over 95% of the nurses remained involved throughout the 20-year period. FFQs underwent validation, and reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. Where records were unavailable, cases were classified as "probable" and included, with approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so categorized. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and hormone use were calculated for each FFQ, with leisure-time physical activity assessed beginning in 1986.

To minimize individual random variation and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were computed (averaging scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could influence results), including age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to examine the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Higher adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was linked to a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States endured a severe financial debacle. Unemployment surged, the housing market imploded, and many major American corporations were left in a state of collapse. This recession continues to this day, prompting us to inquire: what catalyzed this crisis, and how can we prevent a recurrence? Briefly stated, the financial crisis was instigated by self-serving and shortsighted political decisions that coerced banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans to an inadequately developed and insufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to endorse and repack these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’s. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, banks found themselves deficient in capital reserves and passed this turmoil onto the repackaged mortgages they had sold, and then to the broader economy.

The origins of the financial crisis trace back to 1999 during the Clinton administration, as the president sought re-election by bolstering his popularity. To achieve this, the administration eased lending restrictions, setting the stage for the subsequent sub-prime crisis. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation’s largest mortgage underwriter, faced increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans to low and moderate-income individuals and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its remarkable profit growth.” Holmes accurately predicted the repercussions of these actions: “But the government-backed corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, requiring a government bailout akin to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As explained in the introduction, and as Holmes foretold, imprudent lending inevitably led to the economic collapse.

Multiple factors combined to send the economy into a tailspin, one of which was the novel and intricate structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were widely used in the years preceding the crisis, further entangling various sectors of the economy in the housing market. This over-leveraging of U.S. households and financial markets in the housing sector rendered them highly susceptible to even minor price fluctuations.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, leaving financial institutions that had purchased these mortgage-backed securities in disarray. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007, which represented approximately 30% of the USA’s GDP. Ultimately, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold at a fire-sale price, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were compelled to become commercial banks subject to stringent regulation. Fannie and Freddie, with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That section of your story where you spread your wings and take flight, captivating everyone with your spellbinding prose. Or, it could be the part where your readers nod off or click the "Back" button while muttering your name in frustration. Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her screen when she finds herself overwhelmed with Too Much Information, and not in the entertaining way.

Exposition is the bane of writers.

My dear readers already know the basic writing guideline, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still ends up writing long sections where nothing happens or, worse, too much happens. Exposition is that persistent voice in your ear urging you to get the background information out of the way to get to the good parts (as opposed to the voice whispering to tell your audience every detail of each character's past).

Exposition involves explaining what happened to your audience, usually in straightforward prose. In films, exposition occurs when one character shares a lot of information with another, akin to "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, it's the author doing the telling.

Let me provide an example. As you're reading a story, you're told that the heroine met her love at a certain place and time, they married grandly, and then her husband was murdered in front of her. You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to span two pages, with both characters only getting a couple of lines of dialogue each. You would expect the author to delve into the husband's character, showing his love for his wife through his words and actions, and the heroine to demonstrate through big and small ways how his presence transformed her life. A proper introduction to her husband would involve you feeling his loss and growing closer to the heroine as a result. You'd expect to see the husband's personality, her love for him, and clues about her thoughts and aspirations reflected through his eyes. You'd grieve with her, which would strengthen your connection to her.

In essence, you'd expect more substance than a simple summary: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you must provide that substance. (*stares at metaphor, takes a deep breath, and presses on*) Sometimes it's tempting to rush through certain details. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and know he was in the Air Force, now works as a night manager at a gas station, was married twice with no children, enjoys fishing on weekends, dreams of owning the gas station one day, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I viewed two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first, a live broadcast on NBC 4, aired on August 13, 2011. The lead story featured a man named Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife; his name was mentioned, but hers was not. His mug shot appeared, and he looked menacing. The report devoted two minutes to the story, which was developing. The news provided minimal details: he had stabbed her multiple times and been arrested. I thought this was an appropriate amount of time for the story.

The second story concerned the early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, an 18-year-old in the Sharon Woods area who was critically injured. No arrests were made, and the SWAT team was investigating. This story seemed brief, possibly due to his race or the neighborhood's racial makeup. I've noted over time that minority victims of crime often receive less media attention compared to white victims.

The next story reported on a bullet hole discovered in a Med-Flight helicopter, believed to have been caused by a .22 caliber rifle shot. Crime-Stoppers offered a $5,000 reward for information leading to the shooter's arrest.

Another story covered thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon, with temperatures expected to remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The story was brief, but the news likely presented it as a teaser to encourage viewers to stay tuned.

The news also reported a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. The perpetrator was described as a tall, dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. The story devoted unusual attention to his race and complexion.

Another story concerned Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin sentenced to 300 months (25 years) in prison for conspiring to distribute large amounts of marijuana to Ohio from Texas. The news also mentioned his Hispanic background, which seemed irrelevant to the story.

Brothers are bound together by an unbreakable, irreversible connection. This bond encompasses a variety of emotions, including love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers understand each other deeply, and they see themselves reflected in their sibling. In times of crisis, the true essence of this bond is revealed, whether it is positive or negative. These emotions come at a price; part of understanding the feelings born of this fraternal bond is dealing with the consequences that follow. When one brother looks into another's eyes, they see not what others see, but their true self. The reflection in their sibling's eyes reveals their true character, reflected in their actions and their outcomes. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers delve into this theme, experiencing all the intense emotions it brings. Against a backdrop of lush, vividly described landscapes, these two boys embark on a futile journey. Disappointment and pride collide in the climactic scene, and only one brother survives. The theme is conveyed through the direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions, as well as through the narrator's perspective, which shares Doodle's complex feelings and his view of the world, significantly influencing his actions.

The protagonist’s actions are driven by a central emotion: pride. From their initial outings together to their final, fateful trip, the protagonist feels resentment toward Doodle. He had envisioned teaching his little brother all his worldly skills, such as "holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp." He longed for a brother who could share these activities and adventures, like "racing to Horsehead Landing…and perching with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn." However, Doodle's frailty, born with an extremely weak heart, made these dreams unachievable. The young protagonist, filled with dreams, was devastated when these hopes were shattered. Even so, he harbored some anger towards Doodle, recalling thoughts of suffocating him with a pillow. Yet, his heart softened when the small child smiled at him, reminding him that his love for his brother was stronger than his pride. This moment reveals that his resolve was not as strong as it seemed. In his heart, he had an innate love for his brother.

The human brain is a complex, imaginative information-processing system. As technology has evolved from primitive to advanced, the metaphors used to describe the brain have also evolved. Initially, the brain was likened to a wax tablet, then to papyrus, a book, and more recently, a computer. As you explore the brain, keep in mind that these metaphors, while useful, can sometimes lead to incorrect conclusions.

Information processing begins with input from sensory organs, which convert physical stimuli like touch, heat, sound waves, or light into electrochemical signals. The brain's algorithms process this sensory information both from the bottom up and the top down. For instance, when you look at a picture of a black box against a white background, bottom-up processing combines simple information about color, orientation, and object borders to determine that you're seeing a box. Top-down processing can then help you quickly recognize the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the background.

Once information is processed, an attention filter decides its importance and which cognitive processes should access it. For example, while your brain processes every blade of grass when looking down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. However, you might pick out your name even in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results are repeatedly modulated by attention.

In order to process information, the brain must first store it. There are several types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Information is first encoded in a manner specific to each type of sensory input, such as structurally for visual input or phonemically for auditory input. Once encoded, information must be maintained. Animal studies suggest that working memory, which holds information for about 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a specific set of neurons for a short time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained by the structure of certain proteins.

There are various models of how knowledge is organized in the brain, based on human memory retrieval, computer science, and neurophysiology. The semantic network model suggests that concepts are represented by nodes and are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, the concept "chair" might be linked to "table," which could be linked to "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley critiques the looming danger of both technology and the capitalist system that sustains it by depicting a dystopian society in Brave New World. The individuals in this society prioritize community over the individual and are conditioned from birth to seek immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are merely pawns in a grand scheme, confined to a single ideology enforced by the World Controller. Examining the novel through a Marxist lens, one can see Huxley's apprehension about the emergence of such systems. Key Marxist terms like homogenization and reification imply that Huxley's novel is a critique of the flaws in the capitalist economy of his time.

Huxley satirizes capitalism through the concept of false consciousness, where the common people are kept unaware of their true economic relationships. They are primarily concerned with their own interests, a result of ideological control over the proletariat, evident in the conditioning of citizens in Brave New World. The lower classes, like Deltas and Gammas, lack genuine will, driven by hypnopædia to consume and indulge, manipulated by the World Controller. Hegemony, the concept of one group dominating others, is clearly present here. The lower classes are unaware of this manipulation, buying into the ideology of capitalism and consumerism. The upper classes, like Alphas and Betas, are cognizant but generally accept their roles. Interactions between social classes are significant, reflecting the perceived oppression of capitalism.

In Brave New World, relationships between individuals are superficial and lack depth. Even major characters are portrayed as shallow, suggesting that technology and capitalism collectively strip people of their free will and expression. Love and extreme emotions are absent; interactions are kept simple and focused on physical appearances. The contentment of each societal class within their status hierarchy indicates the socioeconomic impact of capitalism. Their adherence to their role in society mirrors Marxist views of the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform to societal norms.

I've been a student at University Park for approximately two and a half years, which equates to about four and a half semesters. Navigating the campus can be challenging for many, including me. During my first year, I was housed in East Halls, the most distant dorm from the center, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from Stuart Hall to Willard building, near the campus center, could take up to 25 minutes, especially in State College’s often inclement weather. An alumni, similar in age to me, revealed that the East Halls dorms once stood apart from the rest of the campus, surrounded by vast tracts of unused land. These former empty spaces have now been filled with sports fields, new buildings like the Creamery and health services, and apartments. As the campus continues to grow, getting from one place to another has become increasingly difficult. What's the best solution to this mobility issue? On a college campus, cycling is the answer, but it's not a complete solution. Students need to use them, and the campus infrastructure must cater to cyclists. My friend, who recently resumed cycling after a break, exclaimed, "Bikes are fantastic. It's the only way to get around!" Alongside its health benefits, cycling is also the most efficient mode of transportation. A simple bowl of oatmeal and a bit of exercise can cover 30 miles or more. Living off-campus, I'm just as far from the center as some dorms. The best decision I made this year was purchasing a bike. My daily commute to Thomas building, about a 25-minute walk from home, can be reduced to 5 minutes by bicycle. The challenge is, Pollock Road is the direct route to Thomas, but it's not always an easy ride. While walking is an option, I'm too busy to walk. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable means of transport. Walking to Thomas every day would add an extra 30-40 minutes to my day, totaling over two and a half hours weekly, plus time spent walking to other classes, appointments, and so on. That's more time than I can spare.
